No findings.

The round 2 URI fix closes the remaining blocker. I re-read [_common.py](/Users/ericalt/Documents/eden/reference/packages/eden-contracts/src/eden_contracts/_common.py:1), [conftest.py](/Users/ericalt/Documents/eden/reference/packages/eden-contracts/tests/conftest.py:1), [cases.py](/Users/ericalt/Documents/eden/reference/packages/eden-contracts/tests/cases.py:1), and [pyproject.toml](/Users/ericalt/Documents/eden/reference/packages/eden-contracts/pyproject.toml:1), then verified the previously problematic URIs directly: `http://exa mple.com/path` and `http://example.com/bad%ZZ` are now rejected on both the model side and the schema side, while `http://example.com/path` and `s3://bucket/path` still pass. `uv sync --frozen` succeeds, and `uv run pytest -q` is green at 78 tests.

Overall assessment: Phase 3 now looks aligned with the plan, the schema-fidelity issues I flagged in rounds 0 and 1 are addressed, the parity/test harness is appropriately stronger, and I don’t see new scope creep or premature abstraction beyond the already-accepted corpus-based parity design. Residual risk is the intentional one already documented: parity is proven over the corpus, not over the full input space.
